{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488257","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488257"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:34:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:34:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"396"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/396"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.01,0.02,0.11,0.65]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"396"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108735"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/396"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"396"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91105"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"527"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"4046"},{"type":"tags","id":"4208"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6088"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6283"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40036"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40048"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108735"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 48-hour history of cramping abdominal pain that has migrated to the right iliac fossa and become constant. She has not eaten for 24 hours due to anorexia. She is 32 weeks pregnant with an otherwise uncomplicated pregnancy. She has no other medical history and takes only pregnancy vitamins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. There is tenderness and guarding in the right iliac fossa. An ultrasound examination shows a thickened retrocaecal appendix with surrounding fluid.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous antibiotics","Arrange MRI","CT-guided peritoneal lavage","Open appendicectomy","Laparoscopic appendicectomy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical and ultrasound findings consistent with acute appendicitis in pregnancy. The classic migration of pain to the right iliac fossa, fever, tachycardia, and imaging findings support the diagnosis. The presence of free fluid suggests perforation and complicated appendicitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic appendicectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the preferred approach as it allows faster recovery, better visualisation, and has been shown to be safe at all stages of pregnancy. The shorter hospital stay and reduced post-operative pain are particularly beneficial in pregnancy. Laparoscopic appendicectomy can be successfully performed late in the third trimester without increasing the risk of preterm labour or fetal demise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpen appendicectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is a valid surgical approach but offers no advantage over laparoscopic surgery in pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E alone are insufficient for complicated appendicitis. While antibiotics should be given perioperatively, definitive surgical management is required to prevent complications that could affect both mother and fetus. Whilst antibiotics alone can be promoted in cases of uncomplicated appendicitis, this approach can be associated with a significant complication rate in complicated appendicitis and as such is ill-advised in pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArrange MRI\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if ultrasound findings were equivocal, but in this case, ultrasound has already confirmed the diagnosis. MRI is preferred over CT in pregnancy due to avoiding radiation exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT-guided peritoneal lavage\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in appendicitis and would expose the fetus to unnecessary radiation. The diagnosis has already been confirmed by ultrasound.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key principles in managing appendicitis in pregnancy include prompt diagnosis to prevent complications, appropriate perioperative antibiotics, and close monitoring of both mother and fetus. The surgical approach should be based on local expertise and facilities, but laparoscopic surgery has become increasingly favoured due to its minimally invasive nature and excellent outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Appendicitis is the most common non-obstetric surgical emergency in pregnancy requiring prompt surgical intervention.","Ultrasound is the first-line imaging modality for suspected appendicitis in pregnancy, with MRI as second-line.","Laparoscopic appendicectomy is safe throughout pregnancy and offers advantages of faster recovery."],"references":["Ashbrook M, Cheng V,  Sandhu K, et al. Management of Complicated Appendicitis During Pregnancy in the US. JAMA Network Open. 2022;5(4):e227555. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35426921/","Candrawinata V, Hanafi R, Baskoro B, et al. Antibiotic versus surgery in the treatment of acute appendicitis in the pregnant population: A systematic review and meta-analysis. Meta-Analysis. 2023; 12:188.","Pearl JP, Price RR, Tonkin AE, et al. Guidelines for the Use of Laparoscopy during Pregnancy. https://www.sages.org/publications/guidelines/guidelines-for-diagnosis-treatment-and-use-of-laparoscopy-for-surgical-problems-during-pregnancy/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91105"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"396"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91105"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-13T10:49:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-13T10:53:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"396"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108735"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"